stylometry:
Janelle, Andy and I did our project on the company that Janelle used to work at, which was Sally Beauty Supply.  Sally sells beauty supplies and products to day to day customers, as well as businesses and salons.  

They problem Sally's was having was the slow check out time.  Everything had to be done by hand, and there was usually only two cashiers, with two registers.  They needed to type in the codes of the products by hand, as well as help any customer on the floor that needed help.  This was wasting time and money for the company.  

We decided to use a waiting line model to help determine whether or not there should be two lines, with two registers, or one line, with two registers.  We had to determine arrival time as well as service time.  And, after running the model for both of these scenarios, we found that the probability people would wait in one line with two registers to be much higher than the probabilty of people waiting in two lines.

If we were to have taken this to Sally's management, they would have seen that having one line with two registers would have saved Sally time, and money.  It would have profit maximized, and cost minimized, while being sure to not exceed utilization.  This allowed room for error and unpredictable scenarios.  

If Sally's implemented this plan, I belive that the customers would be happier, and happier customers are paying customers.
